I can provide you with a simple example of a web application that uses HTML, CSS, and JavaScript along with the jQuery library. The application will display a list of items and allow users to add or remove items from the list.
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
        <title>Item List</title>
        <style>
                body {
                        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
                }
                h1 {
                        text-align: center;
                }
                #itemList {
                        margin: 20px auto;
                        width: 400px;
                }
                #addItemForm {
                        margin-bottom: 20px;
                }
                #addItemInput {
                        width: 300px;
                }
                .item {
                        padding: 5px;
                        margin-bottom: 5px;
                        background-color: #eee;
                }
                .removeItem {
                        float: right;
                        cursor: pointer;
                }
        </style>
        <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
        <script>
                $(document).ready(function() {
                        $("#addItemForm").submit(function(event) {
                                event.preventDefault();
                                var item = $("#addItemInput").val();
                                if (item !== "") {
                                        $("#itemList").append("<div class='item'>" + item + "<span class='removeItem'>X</span></div>");
                                        $("#addItemInput").val("");
                                }
                        });
                        $("#itemList").on("click", ".removeItem", function() {
                                $(this).parent().remove();
                        });
                });
        </script>
</head>
<body>
        <h1>Item List</h1>
        <form id="addItemForm">
                <input type="text" id="addItemInput" placeholder="Enter an item...">
                <button type="submit">Add Item</button>
        </form>
        <div id="itemList">
                <!-- Items will be added here -->
        </div>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, I've used the jQuery library for handling user input and manipulating the DOM. The application displays a form where users can enter an item and submit it to be added to the list. The list is displayed below the form, and each item has a "Remove" button next to it that allows users to remove the item from the list.
Note that this is just a simple example and may not meet all of your requirements for a real-world application. However, it should give you an idea of how to use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript along with a library like jQuery to create a basic web application.

Sure! Here's an updated version of the previous web application with a Buddhism theme:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
        <title>Buddhist Wisdom List</title>
        <style>
                body {
                        font-family: 'Roboto', sans-serif;
                        background-color: #f9e7d9;
                }
                h1 {
                        text-align: center;
                        color: #b8860b;
                }
                #wisdomList {
                        margin: 20px auto;
                        width: 400px;
                }
                #addWisdomForm {
                        margin-bottom: 20px;
                }
                #addWisdomInput {
                        width: 300px;
                }
                .wisdom {
                        padding: 5px;
                        margin-bottom: 5px;
                        background-color: #fff;
                        border-radius: 5px;
                        box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
                        position: relative;
                }
                .removeWisdom {
                        position: absolute;
                        top: 5px;
                        right: 5px;
                        cursor: pointer;
                        color: #b8860b;
                        font-weight: bold;
                }
        </style>
        <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
        <script>
                $(document).ready(function() {
                        $("#addWisdomForm").submit(function(event) {
                                event.preventDefault();
                                var wisdom = $("#addWisdomInput").val();
                                if (wisdom !== "") {
                                        $("#wisdomList").append("<div class='wisdom'>" + wisdom + "<span class='removeWisdom'>X</span></div>");
                                        $("#addWisdomInput").val("");
                                }
                        });
                        $("#wisdomList").on("click", ".removeWisdom", function() {
                                $(this).parent().remove();
                        });
                });
        </script>
</head>
<body>
        <h1>Buddhist Wisdom List</h1>
        <form id="addWisdomForm">
                <input type="text" id="addWisdomInput" placeholder="Enter some wisdom...">
                <button type="submit">Add Wisdom</button>
        </form>
        <div id="wisdomList">
                <!-- Wisdoms will be added here -->
        </div>
</body>
</html>
```

In this version, I've changed the title of the application to "Buddhist Wisdom List". I've also updated the CSS to use a more calming color scheme and a different font. The input form now prompts users to enter some wisdom, and the list items are displayed with a different class name ("wisdom") and styling. Each item still has a "Remove" button next to it, but the styling has been updated to fit the new theme.
